sigma'v values occur among both the coolest
(dMe) and the warmest (active F) stars. Values of
sigma'v increase with H and K emission and scale
proportional to vsini in G and K stars and proportional to
(vsini)1.3 in F stars. For a G star with vsini \textasciitilde{} 8-10 km
s-1 (age \textasciitilde{}0.3 Gyr), for example, 20 m
s-1$<$\textasciitilde{}sigma'v$<$\textasciitilde{}45 m
s-1, roughly consistent with the predicted
sigma'v levels due to magnetic activity (Saar
\& Donahue). All the stars with proposed planetary companions show
sigma'v values typical for their spectral type,
activity, and/or rotation. However, before the planetary vr
perturbations are removed, these stars show significantly enhanced
sigma'v values. We develop a simple model that
can predict the sigma'v expected for a given
star (within \textasciitilde{}40\%) as a function of vsini, spectral type, photometric
variability, and macroturbulent velocity. The implications for
extrasolar planet searches are discussed.},
