correlation function can be used to infer the type of active region
responsible for the signal for stars with v sin i $<$=8 km
s\textendash{}1. A ratio smaller than three implies a spot, while a
larger ratio implies a plage. Using the observation of HD 189733, we
show that SOAP 2.0 manages to reproduce the activity variation as well
as previous simulations when a spot is dominating the activity-induced
variation. In addition, SOAP 2.0 also reproduces the activity variation
induced by a plage on the slowly rotating star $\alpha$ Cen B, which is
not possible using previous simulations. Following these results, SOAP
2.0 can be used to estimate the signal induced by spots and plages, but
also to correct for it when a major active region is dominating the RV
